## **RANGED WEAPON TYPES**

#### **ASSAULT**

* **ASSAULT X:** Assault weapons fire X-number of times in the shooting phase.  
* Units with models that shoot with an assault weapon are still eligible to charge in the assault phase.  
* Models in units that advance in the movement phase are able to shoot with an assault weapon in the shooting phase, but only shoot with **SNAP FIRE**.

#### **BARRAGE**

* Barrage weapons or “G” (Guess-range weapons in older codex books) typically also count as **BLAST** weapons (see below), and can either be shot with **DIRECT FIRE** (treated as a blast weapon) or fired using **INDIRECT FIRE**.   
* **INDIRECT FIRE:** When fired using indirect fire, the shooting model does not need line of sight to its target and does not use the shooting model’s ballistic skill. Instead, center a **BLAST** marker on a specific model in range and within the target unit and roll to scatter (2D6” \+ scatter dice). If a HIT is rolled the blast marker hits the target \- otherwise it scatters 2D6” in the direction indicated.   
* **DIRECT FIRE**: If firing with direct fire, the weapon is subject to the normal shooting rules and may disregard any minimum shooting ranges.  
* Any model fully under the template is automatically hit, models partially under are hit on a 4+.  
* **PINNING**: Units suffering unsaved wounds from **INDIRECT FIRE** barrage attacks must take a pinning test.  
* **MULTIPLE BARRAGE BLASTS:** Determine the location of a single barrage hit as normal.  For subsequent shots, roll the scatter dice only (no 2D6s) and place the subsequent templates touching the edge of the first template in the direction indicated. On a HIT, templates may be placed anywhere touching or overlapping the first.  
* **STRUCTURES & BUILDING LEVELS:**  For **INDIRECT FIRE**, the blast marker only hits models on the top most level at the position of the marker.  If the center of the marker scatters over lower levels, move the blast marker to the next level exposed below the blast marker.  
* **APOCALYPTIC BARRAGE:** An Apocalyptic Barrage follows all of the rules for a Barrage weapon, but uses the clover-shaped apocalyptic barrage marker. Before the marker is placed, the attacker is allowed to rotate the marker about its center to maximize the number of models that could potentially be hit. Place the marker and roll for scatter in the same way you would for a Blast. If the marker scatters, be careful to maintain the same orientation as you move it. Once the final position of the marker has been determined, roll a number of dice equal to the number of attacks on the weapon’s profile. So, for example, with a weapon with the type ‘Heavy 4, Apocalyptic Barrage’, you would roll four dice. Each dice roll corresponds to a ‘strike’ on one of the circles on the apocalyptic barrage marker. For example, each roll of a 2 indicates a strike on circle number 2\. If the marker you are using has numbered areas use those, otherwise use the center circle as circle number 1-2 and designate circle number 3 as any other circle on the barrage template and sequentially number the remaining circles proceeding clockwise. Resolve the strikes as for a Multiple Barrage, as if each were a Barrage attack that had landed on that circle and hit all the models underneath it. To determine Wound allocation armor facing, and cover saves, always assume the shot is coming from the center of the entire apocalyptic barrage marker.

#### **BLAST**

* Blast weapons use the circular blast markers to determine the number of hits by the weapon.  All sizes listed are for the diameter of the circle.  
  * **Blast:**  Uses a 3” Blast Marker  
  * **Large Blast:**  Uses a 5” Blast Marker  
  * **Massive Blast:** Uses a 7” Blast Marker  
  * **Apocalyptic Blast:** Uses a 10” Blast Marker  
  * **Apocalyptic Mega-Blast:** Apocalyptic Mega-blast weapons have three Strength values and three AP values. Correspondingly, the apocalyptic blast marker is divided into three zones, 5”, 7”, and 10”, one for each Strength and AP value.  The Strength and AP of any hits depends on the zone where the target model is located. The first Strength and AP value are used for the inner zone, the second Strength and AP value are used for the middle zone, and the third Strength and AP value are used for the outer zone. Always use the best Strength and AP if a model straddles two or more zones. If a unit has models in several zones, work out the hits inflicted for each zone separately. Note that there will be a different Wound pool for each zone.

