* When resolving a blast weapon attack, place the blast marker centered on a **hittable** model in the target unit. Then, roll to hit as normal using the shooting model’s BS, and apply the results below:  
  * **If the shot hits:** Models wholly under the marker are hit, and models partially under are hit on a 4+.  
  * **If the shot misses:** Roll a scatter dice and move the marker 2D6” in the direction indicated.  If a hit is rolled on the scatter dice, it is still moved in the direction of the smaller arrow on the “hit” dice face. Models wholly under the marker are hit, and models partially under are hit on a 4+.  
  * **Maximum Scatter:** The maximum distance a blast weapon can scatter is equal to half of the distance between the shooting model and the target location.  If the 2D6” result is higher than this distance, use the maximum scatter distance instead of the 2D6” result.  
* **ALLOCATING HITS & WOUNDS:** Hits and wounds resulting from blast weapons do not need to be allocated to the exact models “hit” by the blast marker or even to hittable models only. Hits and wounds can be allocated to any models in the unit. If models from multiple units are hit, hits are resolved separately for each unit.  
* **MULTIPLE BLASTS:** If the attacking unit shoots with multiple blast weapons, roll to hit and scatter for each weapon once at a time to determine the number of hits made on the unit.  Then roll to wound for all of those hits along with any other weapon hits.  
* **VEHICLES & BLASTS**: Vehicles touched by any part of the blast marker are hit automatically.  The facing hit is still determined based on the position of the shooting model relative to the vehicle’s facing arcs.  
* **STRUCTURES & BUILDING LEVELS:**  The blast marker must be positioned over models at a chosen level within the structure.  If the shot hits, only models under the blast marker on that level are hit.  If the shot scatters, only models on that level are hit, and if no models are hit then the shot is a complete miss (it doesn’t hit models on a higher or lower level).  
* **SHOOTING INTO ENGAGEMENTS:** Position blast markers as normal, making note of the total number of models hit by the template, regardless of which side the models are on.  After determining the total number hit, roll as described in SHOOTING INTO MELEE COMBAT to determine how many models in each unit are hit.

#### **HEAVY**

* **HEAVY X:** Heavy weapons fire X-number of times in the shooting phase.  
* Heavy weapons may fire normally so long as the firing model has not moved (even if other models in the unit have moved during the turn).  
* If a model with a heavy weapon moves during its movement phase, it may only fire with **SNAP FIRE**.  
* Units with models firing heavy weapons may not charge in the assault phase.

#### **ORDNANCE**

* Figurine models cannot fire ordnance weapons if they moved in the movement phase (not even with snap fire)  
* Units with models that fired with ordnance weapons cannot charge in the assault phase.  
* Vehicle models that fire with ordnance weapons cannot fire, or have fired, any other weapons that turn.  
* Ordnance weapons roll 2D6 on the vehicle damage table, picking the highest result.

#### **PISTOLS**

* **PISTOL X:** Pistol weapons fire X-number of times in the shooting phase.  
* All pistol weapons also count as an **ASSAULT** weapon (see above).  
* All pistol weapons count as a close combat weapon in Assault fights.  However, the pistol weapon itself is not actually fired and its weapon profile is not used.  
* If a model is equipped with two or more **PISTOL** weapons, it may fire two **PISTOL** weapons when shooting.

#### **RAPID FIRE**

* **RAPID FIRE X:** Rapid fire weapons may shoot X-number of times at their maximum range or X-number times two at half of their maximum range.  
* Units with models firing rapid fire weapons may not charge in the assault phase.

#### **SALVO**

* Salvo weapons have two numbers next to the Salvo tag, expressed as “Salvo X/Y”.  
* A model that **moved** may fire a Salvo weapon a number of times equal to the first number (X) at up to **half** of the weapon’s maximum range.  
* A model that **did not move** may fire a Salvo weapon a number of times equal to the second number (Y) at the weapon’s maximum range.   
* Units with models firing salvo fire weapons may not charge in the assault phase.

#### **TEMPLATE**

* Template weapons use the teardrop shaped flamer template.   
* The target for a template weapon attack must be declared as normal.  So long as at least one model in the target unit is hit, the template may be positioned to touch models from other units as well.    
* The narrow end of the template is placed in base to base contact with the shooting model and aligned straight out from the model in a chosen direction.  
* Models fully under the template are hit automatically, and models partially under are hit on a 4+.   
* **IGNORES COVER**: Template weapons ignore the cover effects and models hit may not utilize cover saves.  
* **ALLOCATING HITS:** Hits and wounds resulting from template weapons do not need to be allocated to the exact model “hit” by the template marker \- they can be allocated to any hittable models as normal.  
* **SNAP FIRE:** If the shooting model is subject to shooting with SNAP FIRE, then all models wholly or partially under the template are only hit on a 4+.  
* **STRUCTURES & BUILDING LEVELS:**  The template marker can be positioned to fire on the same level as the shooting model or one level higher or lower.  In all cases, keep the template marker flat horizontally when determining what models are struck.  
* **SHOOTING INTO ENGAGEMENTS**: Same process used as for blast weapons.
